04682nam a22005775i 9780822389750DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20072007ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223897507 a10.1515/97808223897502doi  a(DE-B1597)553173  a(OCoLC)1168106840  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHQ1665.15b.J64 2007 7aSOC0280002bisacsh04a306.821 aJohnson, Ericka, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDreaming of a Mail-Order Husband :bRussian-American Internet Romance /cEricka Johnson. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (204 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. A Catalogue of Women -- t2. Olga: Feminism or Femininity -- t3. Vera: A Catalogue of Men -- t4. Valentina: Searching for Companionship -- t5. Tanya: Trafficking in Dreams -- t6. Marina: Culture Shock -- t7. Anastasia and John: Making a Marriage Work -- t8. A Catalogue of Hope -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the American media, Russian mail-order brides are often portrayed either as docile victims or as gold diggers in search of money and green cards. Rarely are they allowed to speak for themselves. Until now. In Dreaming of a Mail-Order Husband, six Russian women who are in search of or have already found U.S. husbands via listings on the Internet tell their stories. Ericka Johnson, an American researcher of gender and technology, interviewed these women and others. The women, in their twenties and thirties, describe how they placed listings on the Internet and what they think about their contacts with Western men. They discuss their expectations about marriage in the United States and their reasons for wishing to emigrate. Their differing backgrounds, economic situations, and educational levels belie homogeneous characterizations of Russian mail-order brides.Each chapter presents one woman’s story and then links it to a discussion of gender roles, the mail-order bride industry, and the severe economic and social constraints of life in Russia. The transitional economy has often left people, after a month’s work, either unpaid or paid unexpectedly with a supply of sunflower oil or toilet paper. Women over twenty-three are considered virtually unmarriageable in Russian society. Russia has a large population of women who are single, divorced, or widowed, who would like to be married yet feel that they have no chance finding a Russian husband. Grim realities such as these motivate women to seek better lives abroad. For many of those seeking a mail-order husband, children or parents play significant roles in the search for better lives, and they play a role in Johnson’s account as well. In addition to her research in the former Soviet Union, Johnson conducted interviews in the United States, and she shares the insights—about dating, marriage, and cross-cultural communication—of a Russian-American married couple who met via the Internet.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aFeminismzRussia (Federation). 0aIntercountry marriagezUnited States. 0aInternet and women. 0aMail order brideszUnited StatesvInterviews. 0aWomenzRussia (Federation)xSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822389750zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822389750423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822389750/original  a978-3-11-071183-7  Duke University Press Backlis